# Section B – Development Phases
## AI-Based ECD Decision Support Layer for India

---

## Phase Overview

| Phase | Name | Estimated Duration | Key Output |
|---|---|---|---|
| **0** | **Shadow Deployment** | **4 weeks (concurrent with Pilot prep)** | **Real-world distribution baseline, activation gate** |
| 1 | Research & Data Modeling | 8–12 weeks | Data schema, indicator framework, consent model |
| 2 | Risk Engine Development | 10–14 weeks | Trained, calibrated, explainable risk model |
| 3 | Trajectory & Impact Layer | 8–10 weeks | Longitudinal tracking service, cohort metrics |
| 4 | Dashboard Layer | 8–10 weeks | Role-specific web dashboards |
| 5 | Offline Client & Sync Layer | 10–14 weeks | Android app with offline-first capability |
| 6 | Security & Compliance Hardening | 6–8 weeks | DPDP-compliant, pen-tested system |
| 7 | Pilot Deployment (PoC) | 8–12 weeks | Working pilot in 1–2 blocks/districts |
| 8 | Production Scaling & 5-Year O&M | Ongoing (60 months) | Full deployment + operations roadmap |

**Total estimated time to Pilot:** ~58–80 weeks (14–20 months), depending on team size and data readiness. Phase 0 runs during the final 4 weeks of Phase 6 / start of Phase 7 — it is not sequential overhead.

---

## Phase 0 – Shadow Deployment Mode

> Run concurrently with the final 4 weeks of Phase 6. The model operates on real data silently. Outputs are not shown to AWWs. Purpose: validate real-world distribution before activating risk outputs. Full specification in [ecd_gap_closure.md](file:///C:/Users/cnevi/.gemini/antigravity/brain/382a8dc0-c510-4fba-966d-20b69e5733cb/ecd_gap_closure.md) Gap 2.

### Objectives
1. Confirm model produces sensible probability distributions on real (not synthetic) data before influencing decisions.
2. Detect distribution shift (PSI metric) between synthetic training distribution and real-world data.
3. Recalibrate probability thresholds if real-world distribution differs from synthetic.
4. Produce government-approved sign-off for system activation.

### Deliverables
- D0.1 Shadow mode system configuration (`shadow_mode = TRUE` flag + admin toggle endpoint)
- D0.2 Shadow results stored with `result_status = 'SHADOW'` in `risk_results` table
- D0.3 Shadow period analysis report: distribution comparison, PSI score, tier proportions
- D0.4 Threshold recalibration document (if PSI > 0.20)
- D0.5 Government programme officer activation sign-off form

### Technical Stack
- FastAPI system config endpoint (admin-only toggle for `shadow_mode`)
- Python analysis script (PSI computation, calibration curve comparison)
- Existing PostgreSQL `risk_results` table with `result_status` field

### Risks
| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|---|
| Real-world data quality too low to compute reliable PSI | High | Medium | Set minimum data quality threshold (≥ 0.6 score) per record before including in shadow analysis |
| Shadow period too short for statistical validity | Medium | Medium | Minimum 200 assessments before activation evaluation; extend period if AWW onboarding is slow |
| Government sign-off delayed | Medium | Medium | Prepare activation report template in advance; include sign-off in Phase 6 governance checklist |

### Validation Criteria
- Shadow mode flag toggleable without deployment (config-level change only)
- Minimum 200 real assessments collected and scored in shadow mode
- PSI ≤ 0.25 between synthetic training distribution and shadow-period distribution
- Critical-tier proportion ≤ 15% of total shadow assessments (alert fatigue check)
- Domain expert reviews shadow-period tier distribution and judges plausible

### Exit Checklist (Activation Gate)
- [ ] ≥ 200 shadow assessments collected
- [ ] PSI ≤ 0.25 confirmed
- [ ] Threshold recalibration completed and documented (if required)
- [ ] Critical-tier proportion within acceptable range
- [ ] Government programme officer has signed activation form
- [ ] `shadow_mode` flag set to `FALSE` in production config
- [ ] Audit log records activation event with approving officer ID

---

## Phase 1 – Research & Data Modeling

### Objectives
1. Establish the developmental indicator framework aligned with ICDS/iCDS-CAS data fields and validated ECD screening tools (e.g., DASII, VSMS, WHO Motor Milestone Scales).
2. Define the data schema, data dictionary, and data minimisation strategy in line with DPDP Act 2023.
3. Establish government data governance protocols, including data ownership agreements and consent model.
4. Map existing ICDS-CAS API fields to the proposed schema to determine integration pathway.
5. Recruit and onboard data science, domain, and legal/compliance co-investigators.

### Deliverables
- D1.1 Indicator Framework Document (cognitive, motor, socio-emotional per age band)
- D1.2 Data Dictionary (all fields, types, permissible values, DPDP category classification)
- D1.3 Consent Model Specification (who, what, how, revocation mechanism)
- D1.4 Data Minimisation Audit (field-level justification for each data point collected)
- D1.5 ICDS-CAS Integration Mapping Document
- D1.6 IRB/Ethics clearance application (if pilot involves human subjects data collection)
- D1.7 Government Data Ownership Agreement template
- D1.8 PostgreSQL + TimescaleDB schema v1.0 (scripts + ER diagram)

### Technical Stack
- PostgreSQL 15+, TimescaleDB 2.x, DBngin or equivalent for local dev
- Python 3.11+ for schema migration scripts (Alembic)
- YAML/JSON for data dictionary tooling
- Git + internal repository server (NIC GitLab equivalent)

### Risks
| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|---|
| Existing ICDS-CAS data insufficient quality for model training | High | High | Plan synthetic data augmentation; request historical anonymised datasets early |
| IRB/ethics clearance delays | Medium | High | File application at Phase 1 start; prepare dual-track (synthetic data path) |
| Stakeholder misalignment on indicator set | Medium | Medium | Lock indicator framework with domain experts before Phase 2 |
| DPDP Act interpretation ambiguity | Medium | High | Engage legal counsel with public health data expertise |

### Validation Criteria
- Indicator framework reviewed and signed off by at least 2 ECD domain experts (paediatric/developmental)
- Data dictionary covers 100% of fields with DPDP category classification
- Consent model reviewed by legal officer and approved by government counterpart
- Database schema passes SQL-level integrity tests (foreign keys, constraints, null checks)

### Exit Checklist
- [ ] Indicator framework signed off by domain experts
- [ ] Data dictionary finalised and version-controlled
- [ ] Consent model approved by government legal counterpart
- [ ] DB schema v1.0 committed to repository with migration scripts
- [ ] Ethics clearance application filed (or waiver obtained for synthetic-only phase)
- [ ] ICDS-CAS integration mapping approved by ICDS programme team

---

## Phase 2 – Risk Engine Development

### Objectives
1. Build, train, and validate a multi-domain (Cognitive, Motor, Socio-Emotional) screening-level risk stratification model.
2. Implement Explainable AI (SHAP-based feature contributions) for per-prediction transparency.
3. Implement probability calibration (Platt Scaling or Isotonic Regression).
4. Establish and monitor false-negative mitigation strategy for High/Critical tiers.
5. Quantize and package model for on-device (ONNX) inference.
6. Produce Model Card and Bias/Fairness Report.

### Deliverables
- D2.1 Training data pipeline (anonymised/synthetic data ingestion, preprocessing, feature engineering)
- D2.2 Baseline model benchmarks (Logistic Regression, Decision Tree, XGBoost, LightGBM)
- D2.3 Selected production model with hyperparameter tuning report
- D2.4 Calibration analysis report (reliability diagrams per domain)
- D2.5 SHAP explainability integration with top-N feature output
- D2.6 False-negative analysis report (FNR per tier, threshold sensitivity analysis)
- D2.7 ONNX quantized model artifact (server + mobile)
- D2.8 Model Card v1.0 (intended use, limitations, training data characteristics)
- D2.9 Bias & Fairness Report (performance disaggregated by gender, geography, socioeconomic proxy)

### Technical Stack
- Python 3.11+, Scikit-learn, XGBoost, LightGBM, SHAP
- ONNX, ONNX Runtime, onnxmltools
- MLflow (experiment tracking, artifact store)
- Pandas, NumPy, Matplotlib/Seaborn (EDA and visualisation)
- Pytest + pytest-cov (unit and integration tests for pipeline)

### Risks
| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|---|
| Insufficient real-world training data | High | High | Use validated synthetic data generation; pre-register intent to update model post-pilot |
| Model overfits to synthetic data distribution | Medium | High | Cross-validate on held-out synthetic cohort; flag for post-pilot retraining |
| SHAP explanations not intelligible to AWW | Medium | Medium | Co-design explanation templates with field staff; simplify to top-3 plain-language factors |
| High FNR for Critical tier | High | Critical | Set asymmetric decision threshold (higher sensitivity at Critical tier); document explicitly |
| Model exhibits gender/geography bias | Medium | High | Stratified sampling during training; document in Bias Report; set retraining trigger if bias metric exceeds threshold |

### Validation Criteria
- Model AUC-ROC ≥ 0.80 per domain on held-out test set
- Calibration: Expected Calibration Error (ECE) ≤ 0.05
- Critical-tier FNR ≤ 10% (configurable per government requirement)
- SHAP explanations validated as understandable by 2+ AWWs in cognitive walkthrough
- ONNX model output within ±0.5% probability of Python model (numeric parity test)
- Bias Report shows no statistically significant performance disparity across gender groups > 5%

### Exit Checklist
- [ ] Model AUC-ROC meets threshold per domain on test set
- [ ] Calibration ECE ≤ 0.05
- [ ] Critical-tier FNR documented and within approved threshold
- [ ] SHAP integration tested end-to-end with API response
- [ ] ONNX model deployed to test Android device; output parity verified
- [ ] Model Card v1.0 drafted and reviewed by domain expert
- [ ] Bias Report drafted and reviewed by government counterpart
- [ ] MLflow experiment registry has complete run history

