## Phase 5 – Offline Client & Sync Layer

### Objectives
1. Implement fully offline-capable Android app with local SQLCipher-encrypted storage.
2. Implement on-device ONNX risk engine for provisional risk output without connectivity.
3. Implement sync queue with exponential backoff and conflict resolution.
4. Implement server-side Sync Conflict Manager service.
5. Test sync under degraded network conditions (2G, intermittent, zero connectivity).

### Deliverables
- D5.1 Android App v1.0 (Kotlin, full offline capability)
- D5.2 SQLCipher local database schema (matching server schema subset)
- D5.3 On-device ONNX risk inference module with output parity tests
- D5.4 WorkManager-based sync orchestrator
- D5.5 Client-side conflict resolver (field-level merge + version vector logic)
- D5.6 Server-side Sync Conflict Manager service
- D5.7 Sync failure and recovery test report (simulated poor connectivity)
- D5.8 Sync protocol specification document

### Technical Stack
- Kotlin, Jetpack Compose, Android WorkManager, Room + SQLCipher
- ONNX Runtime Android library
- OkHttp for network calls; Retrofit for REST client
- Hilt for dependency injection
- JUnit 5, Espresso, Robolectric for Android testing

### Risks
| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|---|
| ONNX model too large for low-end devices (2GB RAM) | Medium | High | Quantize to INT8; benchmark on Redmi 6A (512MB RAM floor target) |
| SQLCipher performance degradation on old devices | Medium | Medium | Profile on target device tier; consider selective field encryption |
| Conflict resolution produces data inconsistencies | Medium | High | Extensive unit tests for merge logic; server always authoritative for risk recalculation |
| Battery drain from background sync | Medium | Low | Use WorkManager constraints (charging, unmetered network options configurable) |

### Validation Criteria
- App functions fully offline for ≥ 72 hours with 50 child records without data loss
- ONNX model inference results within ±1% of server model on test set
- Sync completes successfully after 72-hour offline period with 200 queued records
- Conflict resolution handles all defined conflict scenarios without data corruption
- App runs on Android API 23+ (Android 6.0); tested on minimum-spec device

### Exit Checklist
- [ ] Offline data persistence verified (72-hour test, 50 records, no data loss)
- [ ] ONNX inference parity confirmed on device
- [ ] Sync recovery test passed (72h offline, 200 records)
- [ ] All conflict scenarios in spec pass unit tests
- [ ] App profiled for memory and battery on target device class
- [ ] APK signed with government-issued certificate

---

## Phase 6 – Security & Compliance Hardening

### Objectives
1. Conduct penetration testing (web app, Android app, API).
2. Implement DPDP Act 2023 compliance controls (consent lifecycle, data subject rights, DPO appointment support).
3. Implement encryption at rest and in transit for all components.
4. Implement and test RBAC boundary controls.
5. Harden server infrastructure (OS hardening, firewall rules, secret management).
6. Complete security audit documentation for government submission.

### Deliverables
- D6.1 Penetration Test Report (web + Android + API)
- D6.2 Vulnerability Remediation Log
- D6.3 DPDP Compliance Matrix (mapping each Act requirement to system control)
- D6.4 Data Processing Agreement (DPA) template
- D6.5 Encryption configuration documentation (TLS config, key management, certificate rotation schedule)
- D6.6 RBAC policy configuration document (Keycloak role definitions)
- D6.7 Server Infrastructure Hardening Checklist (CIS benchmark)
- D6.8 Data Breach Response Plan (DPDP Chapter VII compliance)
- D6.9 Privacy Impact Assessment (PIA)

### Technical Stack
- Keycloak 22+ (RBAC, OAuth2), HashiCorp Vault (secret management) or equivalent open-source
- TLS 1.3 (nginx/Caddy as TLS termination), HSTS, OCSP stapling
- Fail2ban, UFW/iptables (server hardening)
- OWASP ZAP, Burp Suite Community (DAST), Trivy (container scanning)
- OpenSSL for certificate management

### Risks
| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|---|
| Penetration test reveals critical vulnerabilities close to pilot | Medium | High | Pen test in Phase 6 (not at pilot start); allocate buffer for remediation |
| DPDP Act DPO requirement unfulfilled (if applicable) | Low | High | Engage legal team early; government entity may have different obligations |
| TLS misconfiguration on government infrastructure | Medium | Medium | Use Mozilla SSL Configuration Generator; automated config audit (testssl.sh) |
| Secret management immature (hardcoded credentials) | Medium | High | Automated secret scanning in CI/CD pipeline from Phase 2 onwards (gitleaks) |

### Validation Criteria
- Zero critical or high vulnerabilities in pen test report (or documented accepted-risk waiver)
- DPDP Compliance Matrix maps 100% of Act requirements to controls
- TLS configuration scores A+ on SSL Labs equivalent
- RBAC boundary tests pass (no cross-role data access possible)
- PIA completed and approved by government counterpart

### Exit Checklist
- [ ] Pen test report reviewed; all critical/high findings remediated and re-tested
- [ ] DPDP Compliance Matrix finalised and approved
- [ ] Encryption documentation reviewed by security officer
- [ ] RBAC configuration tested with role-boundary penetration scenarios
- [ ] Server hardening checklist completed (CIS benchmark Level 1 minimum)
- [ ] Data Breach Response Plan signed off
- [ ] PIA approved by government DPO/legal counterpart

---

## Phase 7 – Pilot Deployment (PoC)

### Objectives
1. Deploy system in 1–2 target blocks or districts (aligned with government pilot selection).
2. Train AWWs, Supervisors, and CDPOs on system use.
3. Collect and analyse real-world performance data (accuracy, usability, sync reliability).
4. Run Minimum Viable Product (MVP) evaluation against success criteria.
5. Document lessons learned for production scaling.

### Deliverables
- D7.1 Pilot Deployment Runbook
- D7.2 Field Training Materials (AWW and Supervisor)
- D7.3 Pilot Monitoring Dashboard (operational metrics: sync success rate, screening completion rate, risk tier distribution)
- D7.4 AWW Feedback and Usability Assessment Report
- D7.5 Pilot Performance Evaluation Report (model accuracy, FNR, coverage)
- D7.6 Post-Pilot Retraining Recommendation (if drift detected)
- D7.7 Lessons Learned Document
- D7.8 Production Scaling Recommendation

### Technical Stack
- All Phase 1–6 components
- Grafana + Prometheus (operational monitoring)
- PgBouncer (connection pooling for PostgreSQL at pilot scale)
- Docker + Kubernetes (K3s for lightweight government infrastructure) or Ansible-based VM deployment

### Risks
| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|---|
| AWW adoption resistance | High | High | Involve AWWs in co-design; ensure UI is genuinely helpful vs. burdensome |
| Network connectivity worse than anticipated in pilot area | High | Medium | Offline mode is primary design; pilot in areas with ≤40% connectivity as stress test |
| Model performance degrades on real data vs synthetic | High | High | Pre-register retraining plan; communicate provisional model status clearly |
| Data quality issues (incorrect input by AWWs) | High | Medium | Implement validation constraints in app; field-level error messages for out-of-range inputs |
| Government deployment environment differs from design assumptions | Medium | High | Conduct pre-pilot infrastructure audit; document environment requirements |

### Validation Criteria
- ≥ 80% of targeted AWWs in pilot block complete at least one screening
- System Usability Scale (SUS) score ≥ 65 after real-world use
- Sync success rate ≥ 95% across pilot duration
- Model performance on real data: AUC-ROC ≥ 0.75 (lower threshold than synthetic, given distribution shift)
- Zero data breaches or unauthorized access incidents during pilot

### Exit Checklist
- [ ] ≥ 80% AWW screening completion rate achieved
- [ ] SUS score ≥ 65 in post-pilot survey
- [ ] Sync success rate ≥ 95% over pilot duration
- [ ] Model performance on real data meets minimum threshold
- [ ] All critical bugs from pilot resolved
- [ ] Post-Pilot Report submitted to government counterpart
- [ ] Retraining recommendation (if needed) approved
- [ ] Production scaling plan agreed with government

---

## Phase 8 – Production Scaling & 5-Year O&M Strategy

### Objectives
1. Scale to full state-level deployment (multiple districts/blocks).
2. Establish operational processes for model monitoring, retraining, and version governance.
3. Implement 5-year operational roadmap including capacity planning, staffing, and technology refresh.
4. Establish SLA framework and incident management process.

### Deliverables
- D8.1 Production Deployment Architecture (Kubernetes, load balancing, DB clustering)
- D8.2 Infrastructure Capacity Plan (compute, storage projection for 5 years)
- D8.3 SLA Document (uptime ≥ 99.5% for API; definitions for P1/P2/P3 incidents)
- D8.4 Model Governance Policy (drift thresholds, mandatory retraining triggers, approval authority)
- D8.5 Annual Model Retraining Schedule
- D8.6 Annual Security Audit Schedule
- D8.7 Staffing Plan (Year 1–5: roles, FTE, government/vendor split)
- D8.8 Technology Refresh Roadmap (dependency upgrades, hardware lifecycle)
- D8.9 Disaster Recovery Plan (RTO ≤ 4 hours, RPO ≤ 1 hour)
- D8.10 Knowledge Transfer Plan (to government technical team)

### Technical Stack
- Kubernetes (production-grade) on NIC/government cloud, or bare-metal with Rancher
- PostgreSQL HA cluster (Patroni or Citus for sharding if required)
- TimescaleDB multi-node (if volume exceeds single-node capacity)
- Grafana + Prometheus + Alertmanager (full observability stack)
- Airflow (model retraining orchestration), MLflow (model registry)
- Ansible (infrastructure-as-code for government handover)
- Velero (Kubernetes backup), pg_basebackup (PostgreSQL backup)

### 5-Year O&M Roadmap

| Year | Key Activities |
|---|---|
| Y1 | Production launch → state scale; monthly model monitoring; quarterly security review |
| Y2 | First mandatory model retraining (post-12 months of real data); DPDP annual audit |
| Y3 | Dashboard feature enhancements based on field feedback; infrastructure capacity review |
| Y4 | Technology refresh (OS/framework upgrades); second retraining cycle |
| Y5 | Full government knowledge transfer; 5-year security audit; system handover documentation |

### Resource Estimation (Indicative)

| Role | Phase 1–6 | Phase 7 (Pilot) | Phase 8 (Year 1) |
|---|---|---|---|
| ML Engineer | 2 FTE | 1 FTE | 1 FTE |
| Backend Engineer | 2 FTE | 1 FTE | 1 FTE |
| Android Developer | 1 FTE | 1 FTE | 0.5 FTE |
| Frontend Engineer | 1 FTE | 0.5 FTE | 0.5 FTE |
| DevOps/Infra Engineer | 1 FTE | 1 FTE | 1 FTE |
| Security Engineer | 0.5 FTE | 0.5 FTE | 0.25 FTE |
| ECD Domain Expert | 0.5 FTE | 0.5 FTE | 0.25 FTE |
| Program/Govt Liaison | 0.5 FTE | 0.5 FTE | 0.5 FTE |
| Legal/Compliance | 0.25 FTE | 0.25 FTE | 0.25 FTE |
| **Total** | **~9 FTE** | **~6.25 FTE** | **~5.25 FTE** |

### Risks
| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|---|
| Model drift as real-world data accumulates | High | High | Mandatory retraining every 12 months or when drift metric exceeds threshold |
| Government IT turnover causing knowledge loss | Medium | High | Document all SOPs; conduct knowledge transfer workshops; maintain runbooks |
| Infrastructure cost overrun | Medium | Medium | Right-size based on pilot data; use auto-scaling where possible |
| Regulatory changes to DPDP Act | Low | High | Annual DPDP compliance review; modular consent/data architecture for adaptability |

### Validation Criteria
- System uptime ≥ 99.5% over first 3 months of production
- Disaster Recovery test: RTO ≤ 4 hours demonstrated in drill
- Model drift monitoring alerts triggered correctly in simulation
- Government technical team can execute retraining pipeline independently by end of Y2

### Exit Checklist (Y1 Production Launch Gate)
- [ ] Production infrastructure deployed and load-tested
- [ ] DR plan tested with documented RTO/RPO results
- [ ] SLA document signed by all parties
- [ ] Model Governance Policy approved and published
- [ ] Grafana/Prometheus monitoring dashboards operational
- [ ] Government technical team trained on operations
- [ ] Handover documentation delivered (Ansible playbooks, runbooks, architecture docs)
